HOL-10: JSX and Inline CSS

Define JSX

JSX stands for JavaScript XML — a syntax extension that lets you write HTML-like code in JavaScript
It is not valid JavaScript by itself; it gets compiled into React.createElement() calls
Makes UI code easier to read and write compared to plain JavaScript object structures
Allows embedding JavaScript expressions directly inside markup using { }
Is the standard way of writing UI structure in React applications

ECMA Script

ECMAScript is the official standard that JavaScript is based on
ES6 (ECMAScript 2015) was a major version that introduced many modern JS features
React and JSX rely heavily on ES6+ features like arrow functions, classes, and modules
Newer versions continue to add features like optional chaining and nullish coalescing
Understanding ECMAScript versions helps explain what syntax is available in a given environment

React.createElement()

The underlying function JSX is converted into during compilation
Takes three main arguments: the element type, its props, and its children
Returns a plain JavaScript object describing the UI, not actual DOM elements
Developers rarely write this directly, since JSX is much easier to read
Understanding it helps clarify that JSX is just syntactic sugar over regular function calls

Creating React nodes with JSX

Elements are created by writing tags like <h1>Title</h1> directly in JS files
Attributes are passed similarly to HTML, e.g., <img src={...} />
JSX expressions must return a single parent element (or a Fragment)
JavaScript expressions can be embedded using curly braces inside JSX
The Babel compiler transforms JSX into React.createElement() calls behind the scenes

Rendering JSX to DOM

The compiled JSX ultimately becomes real DOM elements shown in the browser
ReactDOM.createRoot() and .render() are used to mount the top-level component
React efficiently updates only the parts of the DOM that actually changed
This process relies on the Virtual DOM comparing old and new UI structures
Ensures fast, predictable updates to what the user sees on screen

JavaScript expressions in JSX

Any valid JS expression can be placed inside { } within JSX
This includes variables, function calls, ternary operators, and array methods like .map()
Cannot include full statements like if blocks directly inside JSX (must extract logic outside)
Used here to display office details like {office.name} and {office.rent}
Makes JSX dynamic rather than just static markup

Using inline CSS in JSX

Inline styles are applied via the style attribute, using a JavaScript object
Property names use camelCase instead of regular CSS naming (e.g., backgroundColor)
Values are often strings, and numeric values default to pixels for many properties
Useful for dynamic styling based on conditions, like the rent color logic in this lab
Different from className, which references predefined CSS classes instead
